ironmental history that witnessed a perceived scarcity of wood and timber that drove up prices, as well as statute law prohibiting the devastation of English woodlands and urgent calls for the remedying of a resource shortage that was feared would result in eco-political collapse. By considering works including Friar Bacon and Friar Bungay, the revised Spanish Tragedy, and The Tempest, Nardizzi demonstrates how the “trees” within them were used in imaginative ways to mediate England’s resource crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBuilding, WoodenxEnvironmental aspectszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aDeforestationxEnvironmental aspectszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aForests in literature. 0aTheaterszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aTrees in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266417340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442664173423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442664173.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK